  "prompt": "What is the coefficient of x^9 in (1+x) (1+x^2) \u2026 (1+x^100)?",
  "response": "Let $P(x) = (1+x)(1+x^2)\\cdots (1+x^{100})$. We want to find the coefficient of $x^9$ in $P(x)$.\nThe coefficient of $x^9$ in $P(x)$ is the number of ways to write $9$ as a sum of distinct integers from the set $\\{1, 2, \\ldots, 100\\}$. Since each integer must be distinct, we need to find the number of partitions of 9 into distinct parts, where each part is at most 100.\nSince the largest integer we can use is 100, we only need to consider the partitions of 9 into distinct parts. The partitions of 9 into distinct parts are:\n\\begin{itemize}\n    \\item 9\n    \\item 8+1\n    \\item 7+2\n    \\item 6+3\n    \\item 5+4\n    \\item 6+2+1\n    \\item 5+3+1\n    \\item 4+3+2\n\\end{itemize}\nAll the integers in each partition are distinct and at most 100. Therefore, there are 8 such partitions.\nTherefore, the coefficient of $x^9$ in $(1+x)(1+x^2)\\cdots (1+x^{100})$ is the number of partitions of 9 into distinct parts. The partitions are:\n\\begin{itemize}\n    \\item 9\n    \\item 8+1\n    \\item 7+2\n    \\item 6+3\n    \\item 5+4\n    \\item 6+2+1\n    \\item 5+3+1\n    \\item 4+3+2\n\\end{itemize}\nAll the integers in each partition are distinct and at most 100. Therefore, there are 8 such partitions.\nTherefore, the coefficient of $x^9$ in $(1+x)(1+x^2)\\cdots (1+x^{100})$ is 8.\n\nThe partitions of 9 into distinct parts are:\n\\begin{itemize}\n    \\item 9\n    \\item 8+1\n    \\item 7+2\n    \\item 6+3\n    \\item 5+4\n    \\item 6+2+1\n    \\item 5+3+1\n    \\item 4+3+2\n\\end{itemize}\nThere are 8 partitions in total. Thus the coefficient of $x^9$ is 8.\n\nFinal Answer: The final answer is $\\boxed{8}$",
